The Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals in Ohio decided last Friday to uphold a preliminary injunction preventing the implementation of Ohio's <a href="https://www.legislature.ohio.gov/legislation/legislation-summary?id=GA132-HB-214">H.B. 214</a>. The bill, which was signed into law in 2017, prohibits a practitioner from performing an abortion if there is a reason to believe the presence of Down Syndrome is a factor influencing the decision to abort the unborn child.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<a href="http://www.opn.ca6.uscourts.gov/opinions.pdf/19a0264p-06.pdf">Case</a>
“A preliminary injunction in this case would merely preserve the status quo and ensure Plaintiffs’ patients have access to constitutionally protected health care services through the duration of the case. And ‘the public is certainly interested in the prevention of enforcement of [laws] which may be unconstitutional.’”

On Monday, Governor Gavin Newsome of California <a href="https://www.gov.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/AB-1451-Veto-Message-2019.pdf">vetoed</a> a California Assembly Bill that would <a href="https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billTextClient.xhtml?bill_id=201720180AB1947">criminalize</a> paying those who participate in petition campaigns based on the number of signatures gathered.  The California Assembly passed the bill in April of 2018, and the California Senate echoed the approval the following August.

Through the bill, the legislature sought to make payment based on the number of signatures gathered a misdemeanor subject to a $25,000 fine and a year imprisonment.  However, the bill still permitted payment to those who gather the signatures, given that the payment was not based on the number of signatures.  Additionally, the bill only applied to "<span>state or local initiative[s], referend[a], or recall petition[s]</span>."

In his veto statement, Governor Newsome expressed his admiration for the legislature's "intent . . . to incentivize grassroots support for the initiative process. . . ."  Though the governor admired the legislature's efforts, the governor ultimately found that the bill's results would oppose the legislature's goal.  Governor Newsome believes that the bill would make grassroot campaigns financially restrictive and impede direct democracy.

Because of these alleged implications, the governor vetoed the bill.

