&nbsp;

The United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit <a href="http://www.opn.ca6.uscourts.gov/opinions.pdf/19a0264p-06.pdf">ruled</a> Friday to affirm the decision of an Ohio district court not to enforce a 2017 law banning abortions when medical tests show that a fetus has Down Syndrome.

Ohio law <a href="https://www.legislature.ohio.gov/legislation/legislation-summary?id=GA132-HB-214">H.B. 214</a> "prohibits an abortion provider from performing an abortion with the knowledge that the decision to abort arises from a diagnosis or indication that the unborn child has Down Syndrome." Abortion providers sued state officials in response to H.B. 214. Providers allege that the law violated Fourteenth Amendment rights to liberty and privacy in inhibiting pre-viability abortions based on a woman's reason for seeking termination.

The district court ruled in favor of abortion providers, granting a preliminary injunction to declare H.B. 214 unconstitutional and to prevent state officials from enforcing or complying with the law. The court reasoned largely based on the rulings in <em><a href="https://cdn.loc.gov/service/ll/usrep/usrep410/usrep410113/usrep410113.pdf">Roe</a> </em>and <a href="https://cdn.loc.gov/service/ll/usrep/usrep510/usrep5101309/usrep5101309.pdf"><em>Casey</em></a>, which together upheld a woman's express and unambiguous entitlement to a pre-viability right to choose to continue or to terminate her pregnancy.

In granting the injunction, the district court considered factors including the likelihood that abortion providers would succeed on an unconstitutionality argument, whether or not providers would be irreparably harmed without the injunction, the possibility that others might be harmed by the injunction, and public interest.

The court of appeals was left to consider whether the district court made a legal error in granting the injunction. State officials alleged that there was a legal error made in creating an "absolute" or "categorical" right to a pre-viability abortion and pointed to language in <em>Roe</em> rejecting this type of absolute right to abortion. Officials hoped that this limitation would work in favor of the state's interest in preventing discrimination based on disability.

The appellate court ultimately upheld the idea that a woman's decision to terminate her pregnancy is "a right of personal privacy" that has been previously upheld by the Supreme Court. The court found no evidence that the district-level decision abused the discretion to grant an injunction for reasons earlier mentioned.

