The New York governor, Andrew Cuomo, signed a new <a href="https://www.nysenate.gov/legislation/bills/2019/s4572">legislation</a> last Monday which allows a separate or subsequent prosecution of pardoned individuals  when such individuals had, at the time the pardon was granted, certain significant relationships with the President who granted the pardon.

The Legislation (<span>S.4572/A.6653) was introduced to the NY Senate by Senator Kaminsky in March of this year and was passed by the NY State <a href="https://www.jurist.org/news/2019/05/new-york-state-assembly-passes-bill-to-allow-limited-prosecution-of-individuals-pardoned-of-federal-crimes/">Assembly</a> in May of this year. </span><span>According to Attorney General <a href="https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/governor-cuomo-signs-legislation-closing-new-yorks-double-jeopardy-loophole-authorizing-state">Letitia James</a>, it was enacted to "close[s] the gaping hole that could have allowed any president to abuse the presidential pardon power by unfairly granting a pardon to a family member or close associate and possibly allow that individual to evade justice altogether."</span>

<span>The legislation intends to close that gaping hole by authorizing the prosecution of individuals who, at the time the pardon was granted, (1) were related to the President granting the pardon, (2) were employed by the executive branch, (3)  had helped the President avoid potential prosecution or conviction, (4) or had, through their crimes, provided certain benefits to the President.</span>

