The Republic of the Gambia (The Gambia) <a href="https://www.icj-cij.org/files/case-related/178/178-20191111-APP-01-00-EN.pdf">filed</a> suit against the Republic of the Union of Myanmar (Myanmar), in the International Court of Justice (ICJ), for alleged genocidal acts against the Rohingya Muslim minority.  The Gambia alleges that Myanmar is failing to uphold their obligations under the <a href="https://www.ohchr.org/en/professionalinterest/pages/crimeofgenocide.aspx">1948 Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide (Genocide Convention).</a>

The Gambia and Myanmar are both parties to the Genocide Convention.  In Article III, the Genocide Convention prohibits "attempt to commit genocide, conspiracy to commit genocide" and "complicity in genocide."  Any persons who violate Article III are subject to punishment.  The Gambia asserts jurisdiction in the ICJ because Article IX of the Genocide Convention allows contracting parties to submit their disputes to the court over the "application or fulfillment of the present Convention."

The Rohingya are an ethnic and religious minority that primarily reside in the Rakhine State in Myanmar.  The Gambia alleges that the Myanmar military committed mass killings, rapes, and mass physical harm against the Rohingya. The Gambia also alleges that Myanmar prevented births of the Rohingya, burned their villages, as well as forced thousands of them to migrate.  Furthermore, The Gambia alleges that these acts are genocidal in nature because the acts "intend to destroy the Rohingya group in whole or in part."

A UN fact-finding report found mass violence against the Rohingya and report that the Rohingya are "still at risk of genocide." The Gambia is requesting provisional measures from the ICJ. Myanmar continues to deny all allegations.

